com.pb.sawdust.util.collections

Class OrderEnforcingQueue<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.pb.sawdust.util.collections.OrderEnforcingQueue<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - The type of the elements held by this queue.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<IndexedElement<E>>, java.util.Collection<IndexedElement<E>>, java.util.concurrent.BlockingQueue<IndexedElement<E>>, java.util.Queue<IndexedElement<E>>

    public class OrderEnforcingQueue<E>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.concurrent.BlockingQueue<IndexedElement<E>>
    The OrderEnforcingQueue provides a BlockingQueue whose indexed elements will always be returned in consecutive order. That is, if the queue last returned an IndexedElement<E> whose index was 5, then the queue will block until it contains an IndexedElement<E> whose index is 6. This class can be useful for maintaining some sort ordering on results in a concurrent application.

    It is assumed that the indexed elements that this queue will hold are ordered consecutively, in increasing order, with no gaps. Failure to maintain this assumption will lead to exceptions being thrown (elements added whose index is less than the current index), or indefinite blocking (gaps in the index sequence).

    Because this queue only makes an element available if the previous (sequential) element has been processed, it is possible for there to be a discrepancy between what has been added to the queue and what can be seen. For example, if elements with indices 3 and 4 have been added, but the queue is still waiting on the element with index 2, then calling size() will not include elements 3 and 4. The reason for this is so that size() is always consistent with what can be (currently) seen from the queue methods. To examine these non-visible elements, the blockedElementCount() or getBlockedElements() methods can be called.

    This queue has no effective capacity restraints; however, no more than Integer.MAX_INT elements may be visible at one time (even if more sequential elements have been added to the queue). Thus, all bulk operations (toArray(), size(), etc.) will only act on the first Integer.MAX_INT elements in this queue.

      • getCurrentIndex

        public long getCurrentIndex()
        Get the next index for this queue. That is, this method returns the next index that this queue has not processed, not what element lies at its head. So, if a queue contains elements with indices 0,1,4,6 (and element 0 is at the head of the queue), then this method would return 2.
        Returns:
        the next sequential index that this queue needs to process.

      • size

        public int size()
        Note that because there may be gaps in the element sequence, certain elements already added to this queue will not be included in this method's returned value. That is, if a no more elements are added, this method will return the number of times that take() can be called before blocking. Also, if the number of (visible) elements in this queue are greater than Integer.MAX_SIZE, then Integer.MAX_SIZE will be returned.
        Specified by:
        size in interface java.util.Collection<IndexedElement<E>>

      • isEmpty

        public boolean isEmpty()
        Note that because there may be gaps in the element sequence, this method may return true even if elements are being held invisibly. That is, this method will return true if take() will block, even if blockedElementCount() returns a value greater than zero.

      • iterator

        public java.util.Iterator<IndexedElement<E>> iterator()
        Note that because there may be gaps in the element sequence, the iterator returned by this method will only iterate over the elements that are visible (via take() or peek()). If queue.size() == Integer.MAX_INT at the time this method is called, then the returned iterator may only iterate ove Integer.MAX_INT elements. The returned Iterator is a "weakly consistent" iterator that will never throw ConcurrentModificationException, and guarantees to traverse elements as they existed upon construction of the iterator, and may (but is not guaranteed to) reflect any modifications subsequent to construction.
